			<title>4E: Forgotten Realms: Campaign Guide</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?t=60028&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 27 Aug 2008 05:48:03 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[This book is a fucking waste of money.  I know Quelian has some additional dislikes, such as the culling of the pantheon, but I can't get past how fucking horrible this is to really notice the new 'flavor' of the realms. 
 
The entire history of what happened from the last campaign for 100 fucking...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>This book is a fucking waste of money.  I know Quelian has some additional dislikes, such as the culling of the pantheon, but I can't get past how fucking horrible this is to really notice the new 'flavor' of the realms.<br />
<br />
The entire history of what happened from the last campaign for 100 fucking years is &quot;the spellplague happened&quot;  I've got it in a spoiler below that has the entire text, but that's the basic summary.<br />
<br />
The Pantheon section is fucking horrible in several ways, here is a sample for Umberlee, a Sea Goddess:<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2">
			<hr />
			
				Umberlee<br />
The Bitch Queen<br />
Chaotic Evil Goddess of the Deep Wilds<br />
The Queen of the Deeps is a harsh mistress, largelyuncaring of her mortal worshipers’ pleas for mercy when one of her storms whips the seas of Toril into a killing frenzy. Still, hardly a soul steps aboard a ship who doesn’t whisper at least a cursory appeal to her in the hope that her random mercies fall their way.<br />
Her waveservants rely on the scattered alms of terrified sailors for a minimal living, preaching the majesty of the uncaring ocean and the inherent hopelessness of anyone who dares set to sea.
			
			<hr />
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Uh, what is she the goddess of? Bitches? Who is her Pimp/Rapper?<br />
<br />
But oh wait, if You look way later in the chapter there is a table that explains she's the Goddess of the Sea (or rather that the Sea is her 'sphere').  Would it really have been that difficult to explain what each deity 'does'? Some of them actually say, but many of them just give a description of the God(dess)'s personality and leave it at that.  Its important to know what they actually DO when someone is creating flavor.  A sailor going out onto the ocean in poor weather might make a sacrifice of some kind to Umberlee as an appeasement, but if you don't know who the Goddess of the Sea is... you're fucked.<br />
<br />
The book <i>starts</i> with an adventure, which just leaves it as an absolutely horrible structure from there on out.  If you don't know anything about the Forgotten Realm setting beyond having read a few books, you'll need to buy this, buy the 3rd Edition Campaign Setting, buy the <i>Grand History of the Realms</i>, and then download the updates to the Grand History (I haven't looked, but I fucking hope it details the last 100 years better than the Campaign setting.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>everything that has happened up until 1479 DR</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != '') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = '';		this.innerText = ''; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none'; this.innerText = ''; this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
Era of Upheaval<br />
1358 DR to Present<br />
Scholars today mark the calamitous events of the Avatar Crisis in the Year of Shadows (1358 DR) as the start of the Era of Upheaval. Few in those early days could have possibly predicted that the physical and magical chaos of the Time of Troubles was merely a prelude to the Spellplague and the cataclysmic merging of two worlds that would follow. Though the union with Abeir was brief, its mark on Toril was significant and enduring. Even the gods themselves know fear for the first time in eons, for their numbers are diminished and the long-banished primordials have returned to oppose them and sow  chaos throughout the cosmos. 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
Yes, that's all the fucking tell you.  Now, there are a few other parts that go into history that do cover this information, bur you'd hope that &quot;history references&quot; such as Mystra being killed should be actually covered some where in detail in the fucking campaign guide.<br />
<br />
I wish I could give a full review, saying &quot;well, they did these few sections very well, and here's why I liked them&quot; but they didn't do ANY section well.  Its a complete travesty of organization, and it only gives HINTS at information, without actually giving the Dungeon Master any actual information without looking in a half dozen places.  Want to know whats going on in Thay? Turn to the index, then flip to those pages.  You'll have a few paragraphs at the start &quot;shit is bad in Thay,&quot; then you'll have to turn to the section on Thay, that explains what people live in Thay, the you'll have to flip to 150 pages later and read the section also creatively called &quot;Thay&quot; in the &quot;Threats&quot; chapter to find out exactly what has been going on in Thay, but even THEN, you're only left with enough information that you have to make it up on your own.  Its like they have some terror that they don't want to contradict anything that might happen in a novel, or that they don't want to accidentally spoil any information that's coming in a future novel.<br />
<br />
Elminster's section doesn't give stats on him, doesn't say whether he is still a spell caster, it just says he's &quot;diminished&quot; and &quot;immortal,&quot; and that he doesn't like talking with anyone anymore.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now, I can appreciate the concept that you can create a rough framework for players to campaign in, and its up to the DM to fill in details as they want.  That works 'okay' for worlds that aren't filled in at all, but I have to wonder why you'd pay just to get a loose framework of &quot;bad shit happens here&quot; &quot;This city got changed pretty badly.&quot;  I always felt that the reason to pay for campaign setting books was so that you could either play in that campaign setting, or copy-paste sections into your own setting.  Need a set of islands that function like Moonsea? Just copy Moonsea out of FR, apply some name change magic, and you've got a chunk of your own world that the players can romp around in while you work out more details.  Try that with this 'campaign guide' and you're basically left with &quot;a bunch of islands.&quot;<br />
<br />
This just convinces me even more that the future of a good campaign setting is going to be a well written Wiki, and published settings are going to rot away.  If this is what WotC is going to publish for their campaign settings, players are better off just buying a copy of the 3rd Edition version, as it will be far less work for whichever method they plan on using.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
