		<item>
			<title>Roleplay Serial Playtest</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?t=60017&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Tue, 26 Aug 2008 11:38:48 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[After listening to the Independent Insurgency interview of Michael Miller (http://independentinsurgency.com/index.php?post_id=339453) I had to play test Serial. I won't link to the Serial "site" because it's terrible. Terrible, terrible, terrible. I can only hope it gets better. 
 
The basic pitch...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>After listening to the <a href="http://independentinsurgency.com/index.php?post_id=339453" target="_blank">Independent Insurgency interview of Michael Miller</a> I had to play test Serial. I won't link to the Serial &quot;site&quot; because it's terrible. Terrible, terrible, terrible. I can only hope it gets better.<br />
<br />
The basic pitch for the game is that you play the potential victims and the investigators of a serial killer.<br />
<br />
The kicker for the game is that it's taught to you by means of 14 audio files and a two page pdf.<br />
<br />
The time limit for getting a play test done was coming up fast so we put Burning Firefly on hold a week (where last week my Psychologist learnt that you can mindfuck Reavers only at the cost of picking up <i>Cannibalistic Tendencies</i> on his sheet) to run this as a one shot.<br />
<br />
After batting it around for a few minutes We decided that the profile would &quot;chefs&quot;. Don't ask me why -- students, gamers, midgets, and real estate agents were also tossed around. We dwelt a little much on profiles that you wouldn't immediately feel sympathy for -- game show hosts, lawyers, accountants and so forth.<br />
<br />
We made our characters and their hopes:<ul><li>Cliff Collins -- wants to host his own successful TV show</li>
<li>Todd Barlow -- wants to own his own restaurant</li>
<li>Cindy Chen -- wants to bring her son over from Taiwan</li>
<li>Svengali Brensk -- wants to create a dish his mentor approves of</li>
</ul><br />
And then the blood started hitting the floor -- all the characters had an obstacle from each of the other players. The way it turned out was that we were -- hilariously -- one-upping each other on screwing each other's characters over.<br />
<br />
Cliff turned out to be pug ugly, a wife beater, and yet his sweet, sweet body was wanted by the head of the cooking channel.<br />
<br />
Todd turned out to be a gambler, have a vindictive ex-wife, and no right thumb.<br />
<br />
Cindy turned out be an activist in the black books with the government back home, have a drunk wastrel husband, and her kid was enrolled in a government program for kid geniuses.<br />
<br />
And Svengali turned out to have no sense of smell, his wife having an affair with his mentor, and about to be deported.<br />
<br />
We then went around the table with people doing scenes where they tried to overcome the obstacles in the way of their hope. The player whose scene it was played themselves, and dishing out roles in the scene to the other players. Like when Cliff went to pitch his show to the cooking channel my wife was the head of it (&quot;Andrew, call me Ann&quot;) I was her PA and the other guy was the head of the network. Svengali threw his wife out after discovering her affair with his mentor and became a better artiste through brooding, Cliff got predated on by &quot;Ann&quot; without getting anything out of it, Cindy convinced her husband to give up the sauce for their kid, and Todd got his thumb chopped off by mobsters and squicked out his investor by trying to carry on being head chef with the stump and leaking blood onto a plate.<br />
<br />
Simply put, hilarious stuff. The mechanics of it were really simple -- roll even you overcame that obstacle, odd you didn't. The fun of it was turning the dial up to eleven in making life hard for the poor bastard on the receiving end.<br />
<br />
Then there was the investigation phase where we flipped into the investigators and for every even roll on our five six sided dice made up clues. I was the Crime Scene Technician and found traces of blood and tire tracks and so forth. Thumbs up to my wife at being the psychic and getting surly at the ribbing from the detective.<br />
<br />
I think my having listened to the podcast helped here, as I had a vague idea of what to do with the evidence chains. The basic idea is that for four players mean that you have to have five successful evidence chains -- the more bits of evidence in a chain, the more likely it is to be successful. So we were riffing on the ritualistic parts of the murder, the strength required to execute it, the significance of it happening in the kitchen, and the carefulness of the murderer in covering his tracks.<br />
<br />
After that we went to another round of character struggles. Svengali managed to not get deported, Cindy browbeat her consulate into agreeing her file was too old to be relevant, Todd managed to get a respite from the gangsters chasing him, and Cliff got taken to the cleaners by his wife's vicious lawyer Alan Shaw-ing him in the face.<br />
<br />
Then the first PC envelope got opened, and it was my character, Svengali. <i>Nooooooooo!</i><br />
<br />
This cheered up the other players remarkably, who didn't seem to think a tortured artist of a chef was very sympathetic!<br />
<br />
We then went to investigation mode, and did pretty well with the investigation -- we had a witness. We had tox screens! We had more ritualistic elements! And we had a suspect -- my character's mentor. The other players took great delight in saying that this horrible man who stole my wife was showing great endurance while being interviewed and they could see what she saw in him.<br />
<br />
We actually had a good enough case to try and make the roll to see if he was the killer -- and he was!<br />
<br />
The players then voted on whether the survivors got their hopes in the epilogue. Cindy got her boy, and Cliff got his show at great cost to his soul, but Todd got a bullet in the back of the head after stringing his loan sharks on for too long.<br />
<br />
All in all, two and half hours of awesome. There are a few rough edges here and there, but I'm hoping that they'll get smoothed out in the gap between the playtest and production ready phases.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
